column4: Seems much more fidgety in social situations than when alone.
column5: Expressions on his or her face don't match what he or she is saying.
column6: Seems self-confident when interacting with others.
column7: When under stress, he or she shows rigid or inflexible patterns of behavior that seem odd.
column8: Doesn't recognize when others are trying to take advantage of him or her.
column9: Would rather be alone than with others.
column10: Is aware of what others are thinking or feeling.
column11: Behaves in ways that seem strange or bizzare.
column12: Clings to adults, seems to be dependent on them.
column13: Takes things too literally and doesn't get the real meaning of a conversation.
column15: Is able to communicate his or her feelings to others.
column16: Is awkward in turn taking interactions with peers (e.g. doesn't seem to understand the give-and-take of conversations).
column18: Is able to understand other people's tone of voice and facial expressions.
column19: Avoids eye contact or has unusual eye contact.
column21: Has difficulty making friends, even when trying his or her best.
column22: Gets frustrated trying to get ideas accross in conversation.
column23: Shows unusual sensory interests (e.g. mouthing or spinning objects) or strange ways of playing with toys.
column24: Is able to imitate others' actions.
column25: Plays appropriately with children his or her age.
column26: Does not join group activities unless told to do so.
column27: Has more difficulty than other children with changes in his or her routine.
column28: Doesn't seem to mind being out of step with or 'not on the same wavelength' as others.
column29: Offers comfort to others when they are sad.
column30: Avoids starting social interactions with peers or adults.
column31: Thinks or talks about the same thing over and over.
column32: Is regarded by other children as odd or weird.
column33: Becomes upset in a situation with lots of things going on.
column34: Can't get his or her mind off of something once he or she starts thinking about it.
column36: Is socially awkward, even when he or she is trying to be polite.
column37: Avoids people who want to be emotionally close to him or her.
column38: Has trouble keeping up with the normal flow of a conversation.
column41: Responds appropriately to mood changes in others (e.g. when a friend's or playmate's mood changes from happy to sad).
column42: Has an unusally narrow range of interests.
column43: Is imaginative, good at pretending (without losing touch with reality).
column44: Wanders aimlessly from one activity to another.
column45: Seems overly sensitive to sounds, textures, or smells.
column47: Doesn't understand how events relate to one another (cause and effect) the way other children his or her age do.
column48: Focuses his or her attention on where others are looking or listening.
column50: Is too silly or laughs inappropriately.
column51: Has a sense of humor, understands jokes.
column52: Does extremely well at a few tasks, but does not do well at most other tasks.
column53: Has repetitive, odd behaviors such as hand flapping or rocking.
column54: Has difficulty answering questions directly and ends up talking around the subject.
column55: Knows when he or she is talking too loud or making too much noise.
column56: Talks to people with an unusual tone of voice (e.g. talks like a robot or like he or she is giving a lecture).
column57: Seems to react to people as if they are objects.
column58: Knows when he or she is too close to someone or is invading someone's space.
column59: Walks in between two people who are talking.
column61: Concentrates too much on parts of things rather than seeing the whole picture. For example, if asked to describe what happened in a story, he or she may only talk about the clothes of the characters.
column63: Is emotionally distant, doesn't show his or her feelings.
column64: Is inflexible, has a hard time changing his or her mind.
column65: Gives unusual or illogical reasons for doing things.
column66: Touches others in a unusual way (e.g. he or she may touch someone just to make contact and then walk away without saying anything).
column67: Is too tense in social settings.
column68: Stares or gazes off into space.
